      \ker (f)\ar [r, two heads]\ar [d, two heads]\ar [dr, phantom, "\lrcorner ", very near start] & \bullet \ar [r]\ar [d, two heads]\ar [dr, phantom, "\lrcorner ", very near start] & x\ar [d, two heads] \\
      \bullet \ar [dr, phantom, "\lrcorner ", very near start]\ar [d]\ar [r, two heads] & \ker (i)\ar [dr, phantom, "\lrcorner ", very near start]\ar [d]\ar [r] & x/\ker (f)\ar [d, "i"] \\
      x\ar [r, two heads] & x/\ker (f)\ar [r, "i"'] & y\makebox [0pt][l]{.}
    \end {tikzcd}


 Indeed, the bottom-left square is a kernel pair, while the other three
  squares are pullbacks of regular epimorphisms, so the regularity of the
  category implies the data of this diagram. But now the map from
  \ker (f)\to \ker (i) in this diagram is a (regular) epimorphism, and moreover
  agrees with q by uniqueness from the universal property which constructed
  q, so q is an epimorphism. But since q equalizes the legs of
  \ker (i), this implies that the legs agree, as desired.

The universal property of the coequalizer Y\xrightarrow {e} E of a
  diagram X\overset {f,g}{\rightrightarrows }Y is that, for any object Z equipped with
  a morphismY\xrightarrow {d} Z such that df = dg, there exists a unique
  factorization E\to  Z of d: 




